As mentioned above, further amplification is required. This can be achieved with a Fabry-Perot cavity, which can be thought of as a lengthening of the optical path by a factor $N=2{\cal F}/\pi$, where ${\cal F}$ is the finesse of the cavity. The proposed finesse for HERA-X is ${\cal F}=60,000$. With such a finesse, the ellipticity $\psi$ increases by a factor $N = 38,000$ and the integration time therefore diminishes by a factor $N^2$. Assuming shot-noise sensitivity, on paper, this device should easily allow the measurement.

